                 --Strict Typing--
 
It has come to my attention recently that there are some of you
out there who do not fully understand the concept of stricttyping and
why we do it.  This doc will attempt to explain why we stricttype,
and will hopefully give you a better understanding of how to stricttype
your functions.
 
The first part : WHY
====================
 
Why do we stricttype our functions in LPC?  It requires more thought,
more time, and can turn out to be a general pain in the ass if you
don't know how to do it.  However, there are several legitimate reasons
behind we (the management) requiring you to stricttype your functions.
 
1) It's more efficient.  If you tell the compiler exactly what type of
   function you are writing, then it doesn't have to go through the code
   and attempt to determine what kind of function you are writing.
   Also, stricttyped code uses less memory since the interpreter doesn't
   have to reserve the maximum amount of space for each variable in the case
   that it might be large.
 
2) Better for debugging.  There are two sub-sections under this part.
 
   a) More verbose error messages.  If you incorrectly stricttype a
      function, you will get more detailed error messages than if you
      didn't stricttype your function at all.  As a matter of fact,
      if you don't stricttype your functions at all, the compiler may miss
      some errors BECAUSE your file isn't stricttyped.  This incorrect file
      will update and load correctly, but it will crash at run-time.  As
      any programmer knows, it is MUCH harder to debug a logical
      (i.e., run-time) error than it is to debug a syntactical
      (i.e., compile-time) error.  This is true if for no other reason than,
      if you have a compile-time error, the compiler tells you what
      line you made your mistake on, and what kind of error it is.  Once
      you have seen enough of these errors, you get to know what to look
      for and where to look without much thought.
 
   b) Easier to read.  One of the most important things to know
      about programming is that, most likely, you will NOT be the
      only person to ever read your own code.  You might have trouble
      trying to do something, or you might have to leave for an extended
      period of time, or something might come up while you aren't
      here which someone else has to fix.  Therefore, it is important
      to make your code readable and self-documenting.  This is where
      stricttyping comes in.  It is easier for the other human fixing
      your code to fix it if he/she knows what they are looking for.
 
The second part : HOW
=====================
 
I will start this section off with a list of stricttyping "reserved
words" (to borrow a term from Pascal), and continue on with how to
implement them.
 
Qualifiers
==========
static
varargs
nomask
 
types
=====
void
int
status
object
mixed
string
 
How to implement these "reserved words"
=======================================
 
The first three, what I will call "qualifiers," are not necessary for
all functions, and, in fact, SHOULD NOT be used for all functions.
Most of the time, these qualifiers are used in files which many other
files inherit (like player.c or living.c or newroom.c).
 
A brief description of each qualifier follows:
 
static - This variable will not change, and this qualifier is for variables
           only.  Variables of this type will not be saved when the object
           containing them is saved via a save_object() call.  Functions
           of this type cannot be called from outside the object they are
           defined upon.
 
           [NOTE: The first version of this doc incorrectly stated that
           functions could not be typed "static."  That was incorrect.
           The way it is stated here is correct.]
 
varargs - There are a variable number of arguments to this function.  An
            example of a varargs function which you all should be
            familiar with is make_object().  If you only want one of the
            object made, then you don't have to pass a 1 as the third
            argument to make_object().  Therefore, the third argument
            is optional; its existence could be said to be variable.
 
            This is also used to allow certain functions to compile.  For
            example, if a function is stricttyped, and you attempt to call it
            with fewer args elsewhere in the code, the compiler will puke
            nasty error messages at you unless you have stricttyped the
            function as "varargs."
 
            [NOTE: The second paragraph was added in the second version.  The
            first paragraph is correct.]
 
nomask - Functions of this type are typically only used in inheritable
           files, however, this type can be used anywhere.  Typing a
           function as a nomask is a security procedure.  The nomask
           does not allow any file which inherits that file to change
           the value of a function.  Also, these functions cannot be
           shadowed, which is another security procedure.
 
           For example, in living.c, we have:
 
           nomask query_value() { return 0; }
 
           This sets the value of any object inheriting living.c to 0,
           and does not allow the inheriting object to change the value
           of itself.
 
           [NOTE: The first version of this doc incorrectly stated that
           "nomask" functions were ONLY used in inheritables.  That was
           incorrect.  The way it is stated here is correct.]
 
Now, I will move on to the other types of stricttyping "reserved words,"
what I will call "types."  These should be used on every function (but not
all at once!)  You can tell what type a function is by looking at what
kind of value it returns.  You are all familiar with statements that
return 0; or just return; at certain spots.  These return lines will
give you clues as to what type your function is.  A brief description
of each type follows:
 
void - This function does not return a value.  Examples of this are
         reset() and init().
 
int - This function returns integer values.  These can be more useful
        if you have a function which will determine how you want something
        to perform in another function.  Functions which will only return
        a 1 or a 0 can also be stricttyped at "status" functions.
        Those that possibly would return something other than a 1 or a 0
        must be stricttyped "int," and are generally more complex (but
        not necessarily so.)  Examples of this are
        int <or status> north_hook(), buy().
 
status - As explained above, these functions only return a 1 or a 0
           (which can be thought of as "True" and "False" respectively.
           Examples of this are status <or int> north_hook() and
           status is_npc().
 
object - This type is used for functions which return objects.  I have
           mostly seen these type of functions used in code for shops,
           or code which searches through a player's inventory looking
           for a specific object.
 
mixed - Type a function mixed when it is possible that more than one
          of the listed types can be returned.  For example, a function
          that would return an array or a string, depending on what is
          appropriate for your uses should be typed "mixed."
 
          [NOTE: The first version of this doc incorrectly stated that
          "mixed" functions should be used to return 0 or (for example)
          an object.  That was incorrect.  0 is an acceptable value for any
          type; it is the "nothing" or "does not exist" value for all types.
          The way it is stated here is correct.]
 
string - This type of function wiz used to represent strings.  A string is a
           group of letters placed back to back.  Every word is a string of
           characters.  Something important to note about strings is that
           any argument passed into any function is automatically passed
           as a string.  This is important for rooms such as stores where
           you might want to "buy 42".  Since I warned you about this, I
           should inform you of how to fix it, eh?  This is where the function
           "to_int(string)" comes in.  For something like the "buy 42", you
           would have a function, possibly "int buy(string arg)", and to turn
           that string arg into an int, you would call "to_int(arg);".  If
           the string that you pass to to_int() can be turned into a number,
           then to_int() will return it as a number.  If, however, you pass
           something that cannot be turned into an integer (such as a word),
           then to_int() will return 0.
 
Prototyping functions
=====================
 
You may have heard of this as "forward typing" (I hate to reference Pascal
so much, but it is the only language in which I have formal training.)  All
that it is, is if you make a call to an argument before it is defined, the
compiler will barf at you.  That's no fun, but it is a syntax error, and
therefore easy to fix.  To prototype a function, all you have to do is,
before you call the undefined function, place the header (declaration line)
of the function before you call it.  However, you must remember to replace
the open brace (  {  ) with a semicolon (  ;  ).  Example:
 
int foo(string str);
 
status bar() {
  .
  .
  .
  foo("baz");
  .
  .
  .
  return 1;
}
 
int foo(string str) {
  .
  .
  .
  return 3;
}
 
In most files, there is a prototyping section at the beginning of a file
where all the necessary prototyping is done in one spot so you don't have to
go searching for it.  Also, most of the time, prototyping can be avoided by
simply moving the undefined called function to before the calling function.
This is no always possible, but most of the time it is.
 
Advanced Stricttyping
=====================
 
Arrays - If you wish to return an array of any type, simply place a * before
           the name of the function, just as if you were naming an array
           variable.
 
 
 
 
 
 
